x4freetext: Prelim. results compiled in
22320 Entry.
Relative and absolute neutron-induced fission cross
sections of Pb-208, Bi-209 and U-238 in the inter-
mediate energy region
K.E., J.B., H.C., J.N., N.O., T.R., E.T.,
and experimental facility.
V.P.E., A.V.P., A.N.S.
The Gustaf Werner Cyclotron at the
the Svedberg Laboratory, Uppsala, Sweden.
The targets were 200 - 400 mg/cm2 thick discs
of enriched Li-7.
.Quasi-monoenergetic neutrons produced in the 7Li(p,n)
reaction at zero degrees. About half of the neutrons
have the quoted energy, with a spread of less than
2 MeV FWHM, and the rest of the neutrons form a tail
extending from the maximum energy and down to zero,
with a virtually flat spectrum shape. The intensity
was about 1.E+05 - 1.E+06 maximum-energy neutrons per
second over the entire detector area, corresponding
to a solid angle of 60 micro-sr.
The neutron energies were determined by time-of-
flight techniques. The total time resolution was about
4 - 5 ns, with a flight path of about 12 m.
Thin-film breakdown counters, which are not
sensitive to background from spallation reactions,
were used. The detectors and samples were mounted in
two nonvacuum fission chambers. The first contained
Bi-209 and U-238 samples, mounted with 0.3 mm thick
and 70 mm diameter silicon detectors in close
geometry. The second chamber contained samples of
Pb-208, Bi-209 and U-238, mounted together with three
mosaic detectors, each consisting of 26 sandwiches
with an area of 1 cm2. The time resolution of each
detector was about 300 ps, and about 2 ns for a total
mosaic detector.
Fission fragments were detected.
.The large area samples, with a diameter of 70 mm, were
prepared by vacuum evaporation onto 0.2 mm stainless
steel backings, using planetary rotation during evapo-
ration to obtain a good homogeneity. The sample thick-
ness was about 1.6 mg/cm2 for Bi-209 and 0.1 mg/cm2
for U-238. The accuracy of the sample thickness was
about 2%, and the inhomogeneity of the samples
was less than 2%.
.The small area samples for the mosaic detectors had
thicknesses of about 2.4, 4 and 1.2 mg/cm2 for Pb-208,
Bi-209 and U-238, respectively. The weights of the
samples were determined to within 2%. The
Pb-208 sample had an isotopic purity of 98.7%,
with an admixture of 1% Pb-207 and 0.3% Pb-206.
The relative abundances of uranium or thorium
atoms in the Pb and Bi samples were less than 5 ppm.
.The detectors were calibrated using a mixture of
natural uranium and several picograms of Cf-252.
.Corrections for anisotropy of fission and linear
momentum transfer from the incident particle to the
fissioning nucleus were included when the fission
cross sections were computed. Some correction factors
were estimated using proton-induced fission data.
.The cross sections for neutrons in the full-energy
peak were obtained by a time-of-flight neutron
spectrum decomposition procedure. This technique was
not used at 135 MeV, where instead an interpolation
from the measurements at the other energies was used.
Detector calibration      1   -  3.5%
target thickness          1   -  3.5%
correction for FF anisotropy             2%
estimate of linear momentum transfer 1-2%
Others uncertainties are in Subents 2-6.
Data from the same ref. PR/C,53,2911
are compiled in 22646. Full dataset is presented in
thesis (see 22646).
.Data taken from table 1 of Phys.Rev.C53,2911
N.O.

x4freetext: 180 Degree n-p scattering (i.e., the H(n,p) reaction
at zero degrees) was measured simultaneously for the
135 and 162 MeV data, using the magnetic spectrometer
LISA.
The U-238 fission cross section data of Lisowski et al
were used to normalize the data at 73 and 96 MeV.
